<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-894-410  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 894 410.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Telephony  Nov 13 1989 v217 n21 p42(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>It's time to break some eggs; add a few ingredients demanded bycustomers and the ISDN egg could become a souffle. (ISDNapplications)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Aitchison, Ronald G.F.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Market segmentation and added value are new ways to approach ISDN.andO;Regardless of an ISDN application's definition, the demand forISDN will be driven by how well it solves a perceived customerproblem.andP;  At the low end of perceived value, the customer isconcerned with ISDN connection.andP;  Such products include local areanetwork bridges, ISDN phones and terminal adapters.andP;  The nextlevel involves ISDN systems and products that the customer uses tomanage ISDN connectivity, such as specially designed ISDNworkstations that integrate voice and data.andP;  Value-added ISDNpackages, such as telemarketing trader workstations, are the mostvaluable to the customer and can generate the most revenue.andP;  Thelinking of local and wide area networks to ISDN, and theconnection of cooperative work groups, is the foundation for thenext communications revolution.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     ISDNMarketing StrategyValueApplicationsUser NeedsMarket Segmentation.andO;Feature:   illustrationtablechart.andO;Caption:   ISDN application matrix. (table)ISDN application matrix including perceived customer values.andO;(table)ISDN communication architecture. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>